@NODE "Introduction" "Introduction"
@{b}Introduction:@{ub}

When somone enters it will look like the program craches 
and the user will have to write a Password.

Any password is alowed, it dosen't matter what the user writes. 
Only presing return wont do anything and the user will be asked 
again to type a password. When the user has typed the PW one enters
a "normal" shell process. BUT it's only a FAKE. 

After that the user has typed the MAX numbers of commands the sysop
brakes in and kick him back to the BBS. Next time the user reads his
mail one will recive a message that contains ALOT of fun reading :-) 
(read it AN weap!!) The Sysop ALSO recives a mess that contains the
information about what the user did when he come out in shell.

The messages that Sysop recive contains the password and all commands 
used in the door.

This is a nice way to check how friendly your users are! :-)
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Installation" "Installation"
@{b}Installation:@{ub}

Copy all files in the archive to Pfiles
Edit the file Hack.rexx and config after your needs.

Insert this line in your BBSText or where ever you want!
SAC, KUL, HACK `0- |#0Pfiles:Hack/Hack.rexx}
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Requirements" "Requirements"
@{b}Requirements:@{ub}

CNET BBS v3.05 by Perspective Software.
Rexx running. :-)
@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usage" "Usage"
@{b}Usage:@{ub}

Just enter the program and test it! :-)
The files in HackDirs contain information about all directorys
on the fake harddrive.

The user can delete files but when user writes DIR again the file is
still there... This is coz i just send a file cintaining der dir info.
So... If the user palys around for some time he will find out that it
is a FAKE door.

Just set the MAX command variabel to a low value like 3 or 4.
Then the user just can write 3 or 4 REAL commands and the he will
be kicked from the door by the sysop.

But if he just writes commands that responds unknown command the
user can type forever :-)

ALL commands get stord in the letter that Sysop gets when user
quit, hangup or get kicked out from the door.
@ENDNODE

